# Alfido-Tech-Internship

Project Title

Customer Churn Prediction using Machine Learning

Objective

Build a supervised machine learning model to predict whether a customer will leave a company (churn) based on customer demographics and service usage.

Requirements

    Data preprocessing, train/test split, cross-validation
    Compare at least two algorithms (e.g., logistic regression, random forest)
    Report metrics: accuracy, precision, recall, F1, ROC-AUC

Dataset

IBM Telco Customer Churn Dataset

Target Variable:

Churn (Yes/No)

Features:

Gender
Senior Citizen
Tenure
Monthly Charges
Total Charges
Contract Type
Internet Service
Payment Method
etc.

Model Comparison and Results

This project aimed to predict customer churn using supervised machine learning techniques. The Telco Customer Churn dataset was preprocessed by handling missing values, removing irrelevant attributes, and encoding categorical variables. The data was divided into training and testing sets using an 80:20 ratio.

Two classification algorithms were implemented:

Logistic Regression
Random Forest Classifier

Model performance was evaluated using Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC. Five-fold cross-validation was also performed to assess model stability.

The Random Forest model achieved higher Accuracy, Recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC compared to Logistic Regression. The ROC curve and confusion matrix further demonstrated better classification performance. Cross-validation results confirmed that Random Forest generalized well across different data splits.

Conclusion

Among the evaluated models, Random Forest was selected as the final model because it produced the best overall performance and handled nonlinear relationships effectively. The project demonstrates the use of data preprocessing, model training, cross-validation, and comprehensive evaluation for solving a real-world classification problem.

